"But my research found exactly the opposite to be true; 83 per cent of the men initiated divorce."
The PhD student also claims domestic violence — which is rampant in the Pacific Island Kingdom — is also more likely to come from men wanting to control their partners.

Domestic violence is an ongoing issue in the Kingdom of Tonga. Picture: Getty

Sophie said the custom and lack of education and equality are to blame for punishing anti-violence laws and giving power to husbands instead of women.
The custom also prevents men from being able to adopt children and be biological fathers, both of which might be key reasons for alimony struggles.
While she didn’t want to blame religion for marring domestic violence, Sophie added many people in Tonga attend the local church and religious obligations can “form a homophobic environment” — which can be rough on women.
